Implemented a lean, standards-aware HTTP/1.1 web server in Haskell, as part of my Year 4 dissertation, with a focus on understanding tail latency (p95–p99.9) under open-loop load. 
The project is structured around building the server as a clean, minimal baseline and using controlled benchmarking to study how runtime behaviour (e.g., scheduling/GC) impacts worst-case response times—using Warp as a reference point for comparisons. 
Built and run via Stack, with runtime statistics captured using GHC RTS flags to support performance investigation.

